# Pre-election periods

<div class="dfeuk-do-dont-list"><h3 class="dfeuk-do-dont-list__label">About the term "purdah" </h3>

<p>The term 'purdah' is often used unofficially to describe the period immediately before an election or referendum when there are restrictions on the activity of civil servants. 
<p>
Although you may still hear the word 'purdah' used across the Civil Service, due to <a href="https://dictionary.cambridge.org/dictionary/english/purdah" target=_blank>the connotations of the word</a>, we prefer to use the term 'pre-election period'.
</div>

During pre-election periods there are some things that government departments and civil servants should avoid doing or be careful doing. 

Although The Civil Service Code of Conduct permanently binds Civil Servants, the code's core values should be observed even more closely during pre-election periods. These are: 

<li>integrity - putting the obligations of public service above your interests
<li>honesty - being truthful and open
<li>objectivity - basing your advice and decisions on rigorous analysis of the evidence
<li>impartiality - acting solely according to the merits of the case and serving equally well governments of different political persuasions.

## Researching in pre-election periods

Typically, most user research activities can continue in pre-election periods as user research supports service delivery against a defined policy. However, there are some subjects and methods that researchers should avoid.

User researchers working on more exploratory types of research should be particularly cautious in their research approach. For example, you may be working on a policy or service that has not been formally announced to the public or could be considered more contentious in the run-up to an election.

During a pre-election period, you can:

<li>recruit members of the public through recruitment agencies, as long as initial adverts and screeners do not mention or imply that the research is for a government service
<li>invite participants from existing user research panels - this is especially helpful for any sensitive research 
<li>use internal channels to recruit colleagues for user research on internal aspects of services. 

